      "writtenOn": "2026-04-03T17:52:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is 1 second a reasonable default if the test has many contexts?\n\nI don\u0027t see any tests in this patch which supply more than one context.\nThe CI has been prone to fragility and I\u0027d like to see some proof that this won\u0027t increase number of random non-change related failures.  Please add some tests with multiple contexts.",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9a51b871_ad36d990",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 583,
      "author": {
        "id": 601
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-04T08:46:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Rummaging about git it looks like 1s comes from 9225dee9655ce607130f9bab5472441b72e25858. It\u0027s the \"if you are writing your first \u0027hello world\u0027 test then this will work reasonably well for you\" type of default. Unless a system is under load (or severely lacking in performance), I don\u0027t see VPP needing more than 1s to generate, traverse graph and capture a (bunch of) frame(s) of packets.\n\nIf you are writing a complicated test, then setting a correct timeout value is exposed, so that you can pass a correct parameter.\n\nThis method (send_and_expect_multi) has been in use since the original submission of this MR (in tests with the common case being \"send a bunch of packets\" on every worker) and it worked fine.\n\nI can\u0027t imagine how a proof that this change, which introduces a tool to be used by others will not break CI when used by others. How would writing an arbitrary test prove that?",
      "parentUuid": "fc5eaa69_1402ef26",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7242a788_cbd5b828",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 583,
      "author": {
        "id": 10
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-07T16:02:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "The problem is that there is no proof that this code works effectively in the very use case (multiple contexts) it purports to provide a solution for.  Imagination is not testing.\n\nPlease provide tests or usage of the api that validates that the code works as intended.\n\nAdding features that might be used by others in the future is simply adding a maintenance burden and potential foot-gun.  If there is not a current use case for it, then let\u0027s not add more code just for the sake of it.",
      "parentUuid": "9a51b871_ad36d990",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "33423a9d_c0c1ad38",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 583,
      "author": {
        "id": 601
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-07T21:07:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I see only convoluted usages of multi-worker amongst the current test cases not viable for a direct replacement and my tests (which rely on send_and_expect_multi) are using a feature which is not present in upstream vpp and thus not upstreamable. This change is offered as something which is very suitable for writing a \"I want these packets on worker 1..N at the same time and expect this to come out of it\" kind of test. Would you rather prefer this code is not shared?",
      "parentUuid": "7242a788_cbd5b828",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2577a03e_5b11a66b",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 583,
      "author": {
        "id": 10
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-08T14:39:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There is a long standing level of technical debt in the current test cases, especially wrt. multi-worker tests. \n\nI\u0027m happy to accept this if it is a useful tool to help clean up the debt.  It would also be great if it\u0027s use were documented and/or announced on vpp-dev.",
      "parentUuid": "33423a9d_c0c1ad38",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "378be68c_b485ac5b",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 606,
      "author": {
        "id": 10
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-03T17:52:29Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This timeout mechanism is fragile in the CI. Since all interfaces share a single timeout, there is no way to determine if the capture that timed out was the instigator in the overall timeout failure.",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "460edbc3_46e04443",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 606,
      "author": {
        "id": 601
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-04T08:46:21Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "It\u0027s the same mechanism used by get_capture itself. What is your concern here?",
      "parentUuid": "378be68c_b485ac5b",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a9837211_dbcc13b4",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 606,
      "author": {
        "id": 10
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-07T16:02:25Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "How does one debug the failure and determine which context is the root cause?\nIt may not be the last one in which the timeout occurred.\n\nIt would be helpful if there were a means of seeing the amount of time spent in each context.  With the single case, this occurs naturally, but by grouping multiple contexts, the details of each is obscured making it harder to correlate system behavior with the failure.  Thus, in order to retain the granularity of timing visibility, more complexity must be added here.  Overall, I\u0027m not convinced that this is beneficial other than to make it easier to write the tests, which IMHO should not be the primary goal in the CI pipeline.",
      "parentUuid": "460edbc3_46e04443",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cacbb9f7_04b4fd4e",
        "filename": "test/framework.py",
        "patchSetId": 7
      },
      "lineNbr": 606,
      "author": {
        "id": 601
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-07T21:07:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I pushed https://gerrit.fd.io/r/c/vpp/+/45454 which does away with busy-waiting for pcaps. With that change, timeouts in most functions become None, with the ability to override it with a number if there are downstream users which depend on such logic.\n\nTo answer your original question - the logging in \u003ctest_dir\u003e/log.txt is still quite verbose and the underlying get_capture and _get_capture functions tell exactly which capture was (not) there.",
      "parentUuid": "a9837211_dbcc13b4",
      "revId": "17ab012a809206a32efdc293271b1964e212065c",
      "serverId": "6d2eb258-4fe2-443e-8a38-ca81da23d4c2"
    },
